                "name": "Alexander Seinfeld",
                "href": "/profile/Alexander-Seinfeld"
            },
            "answer_text": "I agree with most of what has already been written here, but would like to add a slightly different interpretation of this question. A few years ago I was invited to attend Steven Spielberg's Shoah Foundation banquet, in Los Angeles. The original goal of the Shoah Foundation was to interview Holocaust survivors and preserve their stories for posterity and for scholarship. So, besides the speeches and entertainment, they showed a few sample interviews. These were elderly Jewish people telling about their memories of what happened. What I noticed - and I wonder if anyone else did - is that not once was the word \"Jewish\" mentioned. The only time I heard the word the entire evening was in one of the MC's jokes (the MC was my cousin Jerry Seinfeld). In other words, the Shoah Foundation seems to be trying to universalize the German Holocaust and contextualize it as one of many holocausts. (From their website: To overcome prejudice, intolerance, and bigotry\u2014and the suffering they cause\u2014through the educational use of the Institute\u2019s visual history testimonies. Today the Institute reaches educators, students, researchers, and scholars on every continent, and supports efforts to collect testimony from the survivors and witnesses of other genocides.) To the present question: The question seems to be asking, \"Isn't the Shoah Foundation correct, that the German Holocaust of the Jews as bad as it was is one of numerous genocides in human history, and an enlightened person should keep in mind that greater context?\" The answer, I believe, is that most people who study the Holocaust in depth reach the conclusion that it was very much unlike other genocides in history, as horrible as they were. But don't take my word for it. Visit the Holocaust Museum in DC, or in Jerusalem, or read a combination of histories and memoirs such as: Histories:The Origins of the Final Solution: The Evolution of Nazi Jewish Policy, September 1939-March 1942Ordinary MenHitler, the Germans, and the Final Solution Memoirs:The Last Jew of TreblinkaSurvival In AuschwitzNightMaus Hope that's helpful. ",
