                "href": "/profile/Ara-Sedaka"
            },
            "answer_text": "No, the Holocaust has not been overstated. Other genocides have occasionally been understated. But not by the Jewish community.  It is not the responsibility of the Jews to make sure they are mentioning other genocides, which did not happen to them, in the same breath as mentioning how their own grandparents were slaughtered. It is ridiculous to expect someone to say:  \"Hey, so this really horrible thing happened to my people... six million were gruesomely killed, many millions of others were tortured, experimented upon, held captive, starved, beaten, brutalized, persecuted, and exiled, including my own grandmother, great-uncle, great-grandparents... and by the way, we're not the only ones this has ever happened to, and please let me give you chapter and verse on the others.\"  This question is as if someone came to you and said 'OMG, last week I got in a car accident and the passenger next to me was killed, it was the most traumatic thing that ever happened to me,' and you told them, 'well, that happens to many people every day, don't you think you should spend some time focusing on them?' However, it is true that the Holocaust gets mentioned more than other genocides. Largely this is because of the continuing controversy and political focus on Israel.  I would certainly love it if every high school (not just mine) had a mandatory class called 'Facing History' where they look at all the shameful epochs in humanity's history, not just the Holocaust. But to blame that lack of awareness on the Jewish community is absurd. ",
