                "name": "Rob Menes",
                "href": "/profile/Rob-Menes"
            },
            "answer_text": "The Jewish Community  - and it is not monolithic - has not, and cannot, overstate the Holocaust. That single event changed the culture and the religion forever. The entire body of Yiddish literature and music was virtually eradicated. Most of my family was killed. The balance of power in an entire country (Poland) was irrevocably altered. The response of the world revealed a gross lack of humanity. The Holocaust was not simply mass murder - it was directed at one group, a group that really had very little power in the world. And few came to its aid. Yes, others were murdered by the Nazis, but the Jews were specifically targeted as documented by the Nazis themselves. The real problem is that this wasn't the first time. When the Romans destroyed the Second Temple in Jerusalem in 70 CE, approximately 2/3 of the entire Jewish population in the world was murdered and most of the rest were exiled (a continued presence in Israel remained in Yavneh). This seems to have been forgotten by the rest of the world. However, the recognition of Israel as a continuing political state is one small step forward in insuring that, perhaps, this will not happen again.  Asking whether this has been overstated is like asking a Christian whether they've overstated Jesus' death. Can't they just get over it? ",
